title: Ikea Lack Based Enclosure for Malyan M150

description.text:
This is my version of the Ikea Lack side table enclosure for Prusa I3 clones. It has several elements that others might want to consider in their own enclosures.

I wanted to be able to lift the enclosure off of the printer easily. That required the enclosure to be very light weight. The Lack side table itself is very light, since it consists mainly of thin plastic encasing a cardboard core. Another feature that I wanted was a door that lifted out versus swinging open. This makes accessing the enclosure much easier.

Features:

  1. The side and back panels are made of foam board (obtainable from dollar tree for $1 or Staples for a bit more). Two sheets were required. On the backside a 2 inch gap was left at the bottom of the panel for power cord access. The white color of the foam board panels reflects the light from the added light bar, increasing brightness inside the enclosure. The foam board also provides insulation.
  2. Enclosure can be lifted off of the printer by simply clipping the filament and unplugging the light bar.
  3. Door lifts out as opposed to swinging open.
  4. Required printed objects to build the enclosure are small and easy to print quickly.
  5. An IKEA LEDBERG lighting module was used to light the enclosure. Only 2 bars were required. A piece of double sided tape was placed under the light switch, along with two closely placed wire clips.

DesignSpark Mechanical source files are provided for parts designed by me. The handles and handle back plates files are not provided. They are available at "Yet Another Lack Table Enclosure" by Hagster (thing:1920010). I think Hagster's handle design is really great and used them here.

Printer:

Malyan M150

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

25% to 50%

Notes:

Sliced with Kisslicer v1.5.
Parts made with PLA.
The Filament Washer is used on the underside of the table top to help support the filament holder bracket.

Acrylic front door is 18"x15.75"x0.093". Sourced from Home Depot.
Foam board sides are 20"x15.75".
Foam board back is the remaining piece of one of the two full pieces (~20"x14.25").
Clips were put at ~2" from the bottom and 2 inches from the top of the leg (starting below table top). A clip was also put at the top of the foam board at the center. See photos.

Post Assembly Ideas:
I would consider using latches similar to the front door on one or both of the side panels. It would make entry to the side/back of the enclosure a little easier.
I would also consider adding a handle (or handles) to the top of the table. It would make it easier to get hold of the enclosure when removing it.

If you have some acrylic hanging around, I see no issues in going up to about 0.125" thickness. Thicker than that you might have to adjust or shim out the door clips and latches. I personally would not use a thinner sheet of acrylic than 0.093" (2.36mm), but each to his own. Make sure to make the fit of your clips and latches loose. description.text:
for us few who prefer a mid atx over a full sized case we often have to sacrifice front cooling options for overall case size.

I came up with this design so I could once again add a additional 120mm front intake fan to my partners precision 1500 case (notorious for having zero air intake fans) , Its running a i7, 16gb of ram and a 580gtx so as you can imagine it can get pretty toasty pretty quick in there.... especially when she's obsessively building a new ride on planet coaster [rolls eyes]

I did offer to simply re-case the pc into a more airflow/water cooling capable case but she stubbornly refused [rolls eyes the other way]

aaaaaaaaaaanyway.....

this is a 3 part design, very simplistic in nature but effective in execution (if I do say so myself)

it uses the two 5.25 bays typically only available in a mid-atx case and positions the 120mm fan at a angle suitable to fit but still flow air cleanly.

results were evident when I measured ambient internal temps before and after, there was a 16°c temp drop with the new fan mod which is pretty good considering the fan I used wasnt the fastest in the world (she said she wanted a purple fan which kinda limited my options [places head in hands and sighs deeply])

incase it missed anyone's attention yes in a two bay case it means sacrificing the dvd drive but ffs who uses disks anymore anyway???, plus its a small loss for the much improved airflow inho.

poltur XL

Notes:

forgot to mention...

yes its usable in any ATX case with 2 or more drive bays.

no it doesnt need to be fixed permenantly together, the fitment of the three parts are pretty dam snug around the fan so their shouldnt be any vibration issues and once its slotted in place it cant seperate.

yes the angle of the output is downward so the cool air coming in go's somewhere of use and not just shot straight at the exhaust fans at the back of the case

title: Customizable Battery Tray for FlexRC Mini Owl

description.text:
Those running FlexRC Mini Owl quadcopters in the 'pusher' configuration (ie, motors on top frame plate, pointing downward) may encounter 2 very inconvenient bolt heads, when trying to mount their battery on the top of the quadcopter. These bolts stick up above the top plate surface, and you are left to try to perch your battery on top of these. This battery tray sits over the exposed bolt heads, providing a secure mount for your battery.

If you run only one type of battery on your Mini Owl, then this battery tray can be configured to be bolted to the quadcopter, by specifying a bolt shank diameter, bolt head diameter, and bolt head inset. If you run multiple types of batteries, as in my case, then this tray can be configured to just sit over the exposed bolt heads, allowing for different trays to be easily swapped in/out. (This can be done by specifying the bolt shank diameter and bolt head diameter to be the same value - that of the bolt head diameter.)

This is very customizable, and should be able to be used for a variety of batteries. It is likely that this could also be used with other quadcopters in the Owl range.

Settings that I use for a Tattu 450 mah 2 cell lipo, where the tray just sits over the bolt heads:

bolt_c_c = 43.5; //center-to-center distance between bolts
bolt_shank_dia = 6; //shank diameter of bolt (where bolting battery tray to quad frame) - make same diameter as bolt head for tray that will simply sit over bolt heads
bolt_head_dia = 6; //bolt head diameter of bolt (where countersinking bolt, or making tray to sit over bolt head)
bolt_head_inset = 1; //depth to countersink bolt head to (applicable if bolt shank and head settings are different diameters)
batt_len = 62.5; //length of the battery, plus a mm or so of wiggle room
batt_w = 17.4; //width of the battery, plus a mm or so of wiggle room
base_t = 2; //thickness of the base plate
base_corner_r = 7; //corner radius of plate external corners - must be a sensible value that works with plate width - some experimentation may be needed
finger_t = 2; //thickness of battery holding fingers
finger_w = 8; //width of battery holding fingers
finger_h = 7.5; //height of battery holding fingers
hole_web_t = 3; //width of side walls - should be at least as bit as finger_t parameter
center_hole_r = 4; //inside corner radious of plate internal corners - must be a sensible value that works with plate width - some experimentation may be needed

For a Tattu 850mah 3 cell lipo, where the tray just sits over the bolt heads, I use:
bolt_c_c = 43.5; //center-to-center distance between bolts
bolt_shank_dia = 6; //shank diameter of bolt (where bolting battery tray to quad frame) - make same diameter as bolt head for tray that will simply sit over bolt heads
bolt_head_dia = 6; //bolt head diameter of bolt (where countersinking bolt, or making tray to sit over bolt head)
bolt_head_inset = 1; //depth to countersink bolt head to (applicable if bolt shank and head settings are different diameters)
batt_len = 59.5; //length of the battery, plus a mm or so of wiggle room
batt_w = 30.3; //width of the battery, plus a mm or so of wiggle room
base_t = 2; //thickness of the base plate
base_corner_r = 14; //corner radius of plate external corners - must be a sensible value that works with plate width - some experimentation may be needed
finger_t = 2; //thickness of battery holding fingers
finger_w = 8; //width of battery holding fingers
finger_h = 7.5; //height of battery holding fingers
hole_web_t = 3; //width of side walls - should be at least as bit as finger_t parameter

description.text:
Lots of pet waste poo bag dispensers around, but i wanted one that i could mount on a solid surface easily, in my case i have as shown in the photos a common retractable leash that i mounted this too, but you could also mount it to a wall, door, window, dash or any solid surface. This would be great near the door of an RV or your back patio slider door, or perhaps the dash of your car.

This uses the normal poop bags found here:
http://amzn.to/2i7W260

We used 3m VHB 4991 this is the same thing used on gopro sticky mounts it is a 1in wide x 1-3/4 long mounting area you can buy a pack of 1x1 squares cheap here http://amzn.to/2i7PsfV

We keep 3M VHB on hand in several types by the roll, also available here http://amzn.to/2i7ZNbx you dont have to use the 4991 its just a little thicker this allows for a less flat surface to still have good adhesion, check out the document below for the best for your application.

Use alcohol pads to clean the surface that you will be mounting to allow to air dry If you cant make tape stick you need to go find a bridge and jump off. http://amzn.to/2h4zwik

Nasa helped 3M make VHB tape no joke, don't try and use some other cheesy double sided tape read here: http://multimedia.3m.com/mws/media/986695O/3m-vhb-tape-specialty-tapes.pdf

The heart shape is a functional more than visual thing, if you load the roll correctly the top point of the heart will catch and tear off the bag at the perforation, while pulling towards the bottom v of the heart allows you to freely pull the bags.

Installing the roll and pulling the tail through the heart is complicated for some, but if you just use a pen or a key you can get it with out breaking a sweat i promise.

You can print the lid in another color and add some contrast if you like.

This is a template I use to make travel cribbage boards. I apply this to hard wood and use it as a template on a router table. From there I use the holes with my drill press for accuracy. There is a ton of real estate in the middle for laser etching or painting whatever you want to customize the final product. I have added an .ai file that has track outlines if you wish to use a laser engraver.

Four baubles for your tree! These baubles use layering to produce a two-colour or three-colour decoration for your tree using no special equipment and no mid-job filament changes.

I strongly suggest a layer height of 0.2mm, as that is what the layers are set up for, and 10% fill is plenty. No support, no raft.

To print the snowflake bauble for example:

Print GraphicSnowflake.stl in white, with a one-perimeter brim. Leave it on the print bed.
Print BaubleSnowflake in the colour of your choice, with your usual skirt or whatever (i.e. as you usually print).
Remove, thread with cotton and you're good to go!

The candy cane bauble is similar but has three colours and so involves printing the white, the red and then the colour of your choice without removing anything from the print bed.

Enjoy!

Why are the layered prints printed with a one-perimeter brim? Because I've added a one-layer box around each of the layered prints, so that when your slicer centres the job, that doesn't mess up the alignment, but the slicer won't necessarily start with that outer box -- and it needs to, to ensure the filament is flowing properly before the 'colouring in' begins. Having a small brim switched on ensures that the slicer starts with the outside of the job.

A case to take the MKS board inside and have enough space around to put the wires within.
60x60x10 mm fan can be installed.

No holes yet to mount it wherever you want.

Added a version with 2 pre-formed openings to break out if needed. On the upper end left and right, suitable to guide the cables of stepper and end stop switches

Version 3 got integrated support at the overhangs of the nut carrier in the corners, should be better to print.

Had a look at the USB-opening, was not high enough! has to be at least 11x12mm in height and width. And I build the sockets in the right height. Doesn't even matter to the size, the cover fits as it was yet, no change on full height of the case required -> V4

I'm sorry for irritations: at the beginning I thought to mount a 40mm fan inside, had fitted in height and dimension, but the 60mm is to wide - would collide with a few pins next to it.
So I decided to lift the cover upwards by 5mm, otherwise the 60mm fan must mounted outside (if you like it or need it so take V4)

Because the wires of the heated bed and the power supply I made a larger edition and extended the lower end by 15mm. The wires have a bit stiffness, not so easy to guide into without get a tension to the wires and the boards terminal connector.

description.text:
This is a grommet i made for an OMC outdrive electric shift wire cable harness. GLM Part Number: 27931; Sierra Part Number: 18-2192; OMC Part Number: 379628

this was used on most OMC 120, 140, 165, 170, 190, 225 & 245 Hp Stern Drives between early 1970 to late 1980's

seen here: http://amzn.to/2h4ROQs

Its common for people to break these trying to remove the out drive, or for them to just short out from wear.

This wire goes through the transom and needs to be sealed. We had a short in ours that was in the molded grommet part of the wire, and because a replacement harness is so expensive i decided id make my own out of things i already had so i could go fishing.

I used an old 2 wire US 110 plug off a broken ryobi charger, its a common wire like this one http://amzn.to/2h3sQzo

I cut it to length, used some yamabond http://amzn.to/2hMUsYm in the area that the grommet will be located then took about around 8 inches of heat shrink tube http://amzn.to/2hMXgoh and went up and over the yamabond and heated it to shrink down over yamabond.

Next i printed my grommet out of ninjaflex SEMI-FLEX filament. http://amzn.to/2i8eGe2

i then covered that now shrunken heatshrink tube with yamabond and run the printed grommet up over the tube it should be a snug fit i had to warm the grommet some before going over the heat shrink, the yamabond should act like lube. But test fit it first if its too loose add another layer of heat shrink and yamabond like the first and try again.

Install some new plug ends! the ends of the wire are just common bullet connectors like these: http://amzn.to/2i89reb

Cover the grommet with yamabond and lace it through the transom and press the grommet into place so its flush like the original.

now check for leaks, mine seems to still float, so now lets get back to fishing already....
